<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="211" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[160,1157,142,1243]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,482,177,203]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
Female 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[259,381,177,203]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
(
<figureCitation box="[267,365,177,203]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1050,1073]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,191,1006]" captionTargetId="figure-170@5.[162,1154,142,1018]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov. (a, b) Habitus of paratype female in dorsal and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758319" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758319/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 2</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Length
</emphasis>
: 
<quantity box="[499,617,178,203]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.654" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" unit="mm" value="26.54">26.54 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[631,704,178,203]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Width</emphasis>
: 
<quantity box="[721,839,178,203]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.257" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" unit="mm" value="12.57">12.57 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[854,934,178,203]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Colour</emphasis>
: Completely black. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,223,212,237]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Head</emphasis>
: Clypeus triangular, transverse (3 times wider than long), slightly constricted laterally, rounded apically; surface densely rugopunctate, with scattered setae on sides separated by a glabrous middle area. Frontoclypeal suture with transverse, short, flattened, weakly bilobed tubercle. Frons slightly concave, scarcely, irregularly punctate; interocular width equals 4.0 transverse eye diameters. Ocular canthus subrectangular, transverse, glabrous. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[418,562,386,411]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Mouthparts</emphasis>
: Labrum trapezoidal, truncated at apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[168,268,420,445]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1090,1113]" captionTargetBox="[166,1145,146,1050]" captionTargetId="figure-188@9.[166,1149,142,1058]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 6. Labrum in dorsal view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758331" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758331/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 6</figureCitation>
(b)). Mandibles bidentate; teeth lobed, exposed laterally to clypeus; basal tooth larger in size compared to apical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[699,795,455,480]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="10.[160,225,1156,1179]" captionTargetBox="[169,1149,148,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-156@10.[166,1149,142,1125]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 7. Right mandible in dorsal view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicate the apical tooth in (a–e), striate molar in (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758333/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(b)). Maxillary galea rounded at apex; inner margin with 3 small, pointed teeth located at middle of galea; stipe weakly produced laterally (shorter in length than maxillary palpomere I) (
<figureCitation box="[910,1004,524,549]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1161,1184]" captionTargetBox="[167,1127,143,1126]" captionTargetId="figure-61@11.[166,1149,142,1129]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 8. Right maxilla in ventral view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicating triangular galea in (a), elongate maxillary palpomere II in (b), lobed inner margin of galea and stipe with triangular lobe in (c), pointed and triangular teeth on galea in (d), scythe-shape d teeth and rounded inner margin of galea in (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758335/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(b)). Maxillary palpomere II beaker-shaped, elongate (2.8 times longer than width at middle) (
<figureCitation box="[1062,1156,559,584]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1161,1184]" captionTargetBox="[167,1127,143,1126]" captionTargetId="figure-61@11.[166,1149,142,1129]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 8. Right maxilla in ventral view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicating triangular galea in (a), elongate maxillary palpomere II in (b), lobed inner margin of galea and stipe with triangular lobe in (c), pointed and triangular teeth on galea in (d), scythe-shape d teeth and rounded inner margin of galea in (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758335/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(b)). Labium suboval, with subapical sides constricted, apex rounded; surface surrounded with large, deep, coalescent, bristled punctures; disc scarcely punctate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,244,663,688]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum rounded laterally in dorsal view, weakly convex in lateral view; anterior tubercle obsolete; posterior border interrupted at middle; anterior area densely covered with large, deep, C-shaped punctures; punctures gradually becoming small, shallow towards posterior area; anterior corners scarcely punctate (punctures predominantly spaced about 1 diameter of punctures (
<figureCitation box="[905,1030,802,827]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figures 11</figureCitation>
(c) and 12 (c)). Scutellar plate parabolic in shape, glabrous, scarcely punctate; punctures confined to anterior area, scattered about 1 diameter of punctures. Elytra longitudinally covered with 9 well-marked striae (1 sutural, 4 discal, 4 lateral); each stria with a row of large, ocellate, deep punctures; anterior area of first interstria with 9 large, deep, ocellated punctures; other interstriae finely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[915,1034,975,1000]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="15.[160,225,1189,1212]" captionTargetBox="[167,1149,146,1154]" captionTargetId="figure-100@15.[166,1149,142,1157]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 12. Females of Gibboryctes species with detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs in lateral view and left elytra in dorsal view, respectively. (a,b) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (c,d) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (e,f) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov. Jsi, juxtasutural interstria. Arrow indicates coalescent punctures in (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758343" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758343/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 12</figureCitation>
(d)). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1093,1149,975,1000]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Legs</emphasis>
: Mesotibial outer carinae with 15 stout spinules like setae (6 on basal carina, 9 on medial carina). Metatibial outer carinae with short, stout spinules. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1027,1150,1044,1069]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tergite VIII rugopuctate on sides, punctate on disc. Ventrites II–V densely rugopunctate on sides, finely punctate on disc; ventrites II–V with a row of setigerous punctures confined to sides; ventrite VI parabolic in shape, surrounded with rugopunctures, smooth on discal area, covered with short setae on posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[168,283,1218,1243]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="16.[160,225,1058,1081]" captionTargetBox="[166,1146,145,1023]" captionTargetId="figure-155@16.[166,1149,142,1026]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 13. Detail of ventrites I–VI of females. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicate the proportions of ventrites V and VI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758345" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758345/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Figure 13</figureCitation>
(b)).
</paragraph>
